             and John Brown; they are <rs id="t18130714-97-viclabel564" type="occupation">general merchant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18130714-97-victim957 t18130714-97-viclabel564"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18130714-97-victim959 t18130714-97-viclabel564"></join>s. We had hogsheads of hogs-lard in our warehouse; one of the bladders of hogs-lard was taken out of the hogshead.</p>
               <p>MR. DREW. The prisoner offered me a bladder of hogslard at nine-pence a pound; from the price that he asked for it I considered he did not come honestly by it; an officer came by, I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>- CAVILLIAR. I apprehended the prisoner on the 1st of May; I asked him how he came by the lard; he said he bought it of 
               <persName id="t18130714-97-person962">
                  John 
                  Dodd
               <interp inst="t18130714-97-person962" type="surname" value="Dodd"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130714-97-person962" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130714-97-person962" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             in Hackney-road; he was driving the Cambridge waggon.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18130714-97-person963">
                  SAMUEL 
                  SUMMERS
               <interp inst="t18130714-97-person963" type="surname" value="SUMMERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130714-97-person963" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130714-97-person963" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an errand-boy to Messrs. Anderson and Brown. I know that hogs-lard was in the cellar; it was taken out of a hogshead for a sample, and it being a little one I took notice of it; I believe that to be the one. The prisoner had free access to the warehouse.</p>
               <p>Mr. Drew. That is the lard he offered me for nine-pence a pound.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I bought the lard, thinking I might get a shilling or two by it.</p>
